safe-add(x): my-if(x number?, x + 1, 0) # no warning # NON-STRUCTURAL — not a brancher; narrowing does NOT fire
always-true(c, t, _f): t ` { type: "(number | string) → number" }
safe2(x): always-true(x number?, x + 1, 0) # x is still number|string in body The second example does not produce false-positive warnings because always-true is not narrowing-aware — x retains its declared type number | string throughout the body, which is type-safe here.
